<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="103" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Based on the specimens studied here, the new genus is restricted to the lowland areas of the Amazonian basin of Peru.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="103" type="bionomics">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Bionomics.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Based on the available label data, the genus occurs in forested areas (100-420 m elevation) and has so far only been collected by flight intercept traps.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="103" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="103">
The genus name is a combination of 
<normalizedToken originalValue="‘Amazon’">'Amazon'</normalizedToken>
and the genus name 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Heterothops" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Heterothops" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Heterothops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which the new genus strongly resembles superficially.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="103" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="103">
The new genus is certainly morphologically distinct among other members of the subfamily 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Staphylininae">Staphylininae</taxonomicName>
and family 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Staphylinidae</taxonomicName>
. Noteworthy is the secondary sexual dimorphism exhibited by 
<taxonomicName authority="Shaw, Orlov &amp; Solodovnikov, 2020" authorityName="Shaw &amp; Orlov &amp; Solodovnikov" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Amazonothops" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Amazonothops" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Amazonothops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In males, the mesotrochanter and first mesotarsomere have distinct black combs which are completely lacking in females (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Morphology of Amazonothops aslaki gen. et sp. nov. A tergite VII B tergite VII C abdominal apex (tergites VII and VIII) D empodium of mesotarsi E empodium of metatarsi F mesotarsi (male) G mesotrochanter (male) H mesoleg (male). ES, Empodial setae; FS, Foliose setae; MS, Mesotarsomere; MSTr, Mesotrochanter; SS, Simple setae." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.904.48592.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/372639" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">4F, G, H</figureCitation>
). The function, if any, of the combs remains unknown but very similar combs are commonly found within 
<taxonomicName lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="tribe" tribe="Amblyopinini">Amblyopinini</taxonomicName>
, e.g., recently illustrated for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fauvel" authorityYear="1883" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Myotyphlus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Myotyphlus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Myotyphlus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Fauvel, 1883 (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1111/aen.12233" author="Solodovnikov, A" journalOrPublisher="Austral Entomology" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" pagination="311 - 321" refId="B12" refString="Solodovnikov, A, Jenkins Shaw, J, 2017. The remarkable Australian rove beetle genus Myotyphlus: its cryptic diversity and significance for exploring mutualism among insects and mammals (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae). Austral Entomology 56: 311 - 321, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1111/aen.12233" title="The remarkable Australian rove beetle genus Myotyphlus: its cryptic diversity and significance for exploring mutualism among insects and mammals (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.1111/aen.12233" volume="56" year="2017">Solodovnikov and Jenkins Shaw 2017</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
